  "prompt": "What is contingent asset and contingent liability?",
  "response": "Contingent assets and contingent liabilities are potential future assets or liabilities that may arise depending on the outcome of an uncertain future event.\n\n**Contingent Asset:**\nA contingent asset is a possible asset that arises from past events and whose existence will be confirmed only by the occurrence or non-occurrence of one or more uncertain future events not wholly within the control of the entity. It is a potential economic benefit that could be realized if specific conditions are met. However, contingent assets are not recognized in financial statements because it would violate the principle of conservatism and could lead to overstatement of assets. They are disclosed in the notes to the financial statements if the inflow of benefits is probable.\n\n**Example:** A company has filed a lawsuit seeking damages from another party. If the company expects to win the case and receive the damages, this potential compensation is considered a contingent asset.\n\n**Contingent Liability:**\nA contingent liability is a potential obligation that arises from past events and whose existence will be confirmed only by the occurrence or non-occurrence of one or more uncertain future events not wholly within the control of the entity. Contingent liabilities represent a risk of future financial loss. Unlike contingent assets, contingent liabilities are required to be disclosed in the financial statements if the risk of loss is more than remote but less than probable. If the likelihood of the future event is probable and the amount can be reasonably estimated, the liability is recorded in the financial statements.\n\n**Example:** A company has been sued and the outcome is uncertain. If the lawsuit is resolved against the company, it may have to pay damages. This potential obligation is considered a contingent liability.\n\nThe key difference between contingent assets and contingent liabilities is that contingent assets represent potential future economic benefits, while contingent liabilities represent potential future obligations that may result in financial loss. Both are subject to the uncertainty of future events and are treated accordingly in terms of disclosure and recognition in financial reporting.",
